In [8]:
#convert prosper rating into ordered categorical types
rating = ['AA','A','B','C','D','E','HR']
rating = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = rating )
df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(rating)
In [9]:
status = ['Full-time','Part-time','Employed','Self-employed','Retired','Other','Not employed','Not available']
status = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = status )
df['EmploymentStatus'] = df['EmploymentStatus'].astype(status)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interesed in what features can affect Borrower Rate for the loan

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the higher the loan term is the higher the rate, also I think that the original amount and the monthly payment are a huge factor in the determinig the rate

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Borrower Rate.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of Borrower Rate looks bimodal and Most of the values are between 0.25 and 0.1, There is no need to perform any additional transforamtion.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The Employment status duration and monthly loan payment is right skewed. The least Porsper loan rating is AA which we can suppose of their high value. There is no need to perform any tranformation

Bivariate Exploration¶

To start off with, I want to look at the pairwise correlations present between features in the data.

categoric_vars = ['Term', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'EmploymentStatus']
In [20]:
# correlation plot
plt.figure(figsize = [8, 5])

In [21]:
#Using samples will make the plot clearer
samples = np.random.choice(df.shape[0], 2000, replace = False)
sample = df.loc[samples,:]

g = sb.PairGrid(data = sample , vars = numeric_vars)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20);
g.map_offdiag(sb.regplot ,scatter_kws={'alpha':0.01});

We can see that the correlation coeffient between Borrower Rate and Original Amount and Monthly Loan Payment is high which supports my expectations and from the scatter plot we can see they are inversly proportional to the Rate. Also we can see that the Employment status Duration does not have a huge effect on the Borrower Rate.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation=40)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df, y_vars = ['BorrowerRate', 'LoanOriginalAmount','MonthlyLoanPayment'], x_vars = categoric_vars,
                size = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The Borrower Rate is inversly proportional to the Loan Original Amount and Monthly Loan Payment which was expected but what is intersting is the Employment Satatus Duration as it does not have an effect on the Borrower Rate as the correlation coeffient is 0.02 Also the Borrower Rate increases with the lower prosper ratings, But the most intersting outcome is that the term as we can see that the Borrower Rate mean for the 3 trems is so close

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

One interesting outcome is that Full Time Applicants does not apply for the 60 Month loan as the Employed Applicant. Also the Employend Applicant has the higher Loan Original Amount. Another one is the Monthly Loan Payment which doesnot change by far with different Employment Status. The last relation I find it interesting is between the Prosper Rating and the Loan Original Amount as it seems to be the same except for E and HR have lower Original Amount, It is strange as the higher prosper rating is supposed to have higher Original Amount.
